WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:04.000
♪ ♪

00:08.000 --> 00:09.333
GREG:
<i>So, why couldn't we just have</i>

00:09.417 --> 00:11.083
dinner with your boss
at a nice restaurant?

00:11.166 --> 00:12.959
Because I'm trying
to make partner, Greg.

00:13.041 --> 00:14.458
I need him to see the real me.

00:14.542 --> 00:17.458
Then why did we put away
all the photos of Lark?

00:17.542 --> 00:19.000
Oh, he doesn't know
I have a kid.

00:19.083 --> 00:20.250
Also, he thinks we're vegan,

00:20.333 --> 00:21.917
so the food's gonna suck--
sorry.

00:22.000 --> 00:24.375
(doorbell rings)

00:24.458 --> 00:25.625
(laughing):
I mean, come on.

00:25.709 --> 00:27.750
That is, like, legit crazy.

00:27.834 --> 00:29.625
I cannot believe you went
to Camp Running Wolf, too.

00:29.709 --> 00:31.792
Now, is this the camp
where the kid got murdered,

00:31.875 --> 00:33.083
or the one
with the cool hot dogs?

00:33.166 --> 00:35.125
Same camp. Hey, Paul.

00:35.208 --> 00:37.709
Hey, Paul, do you like
mashed potatoes?

00:37.792 --> 00:39.417
Oh, we don't have any
mashed potatoes, hon.

00:39.500 --> 00:40.959
JEN AND PAUL:
Hot potato, hot potato,

00:41.041 --> 00:42.250
we'll be friends forever.

00:42.333 --> 00:44.250
Hot potato, hot potato,
we'll be friends for life.

00:44.333 --> 00:46.750
Mush it, dash it,
mix it, mash it.

00:46.834 --> 00:48.875
Never use a knife.

00:48.959 --> 00:51.458
Okay, if you can lay down
some lyrics,

00:51.542 --> 00:53.166
I can beatbox.

00:53.250 --> 00:55.208
And that's when I realized

00:55.291 --> 00:57.208
somebody has to rescue

00:57.291 --> 00:58.500
the teacup poodles.

00:58.583 --> 01:00.041
-Oh, absolutely.
-Yeah.

01:00.125 --> 01:01.458
-Of course, yeah.
-Absolutely.

01:01.542 --> 01:03.625
How many poodles
have you rescued?

01:03.709 --> 01:06.750
Three. We're very picky.

01:06.834 --> 01:09.000
Mm-hmm. I love
a discerning charity.

01:09.083 --> 01:10.625
Yeah, do you take donations?

01:10.709 --> 01:12.875
As a matter of fact, I do.

01:12.959 --> 01:13.917
Great.

01:14.000 --> 01:15.208
I'm gonna get my checkbook.

01:15.291 --> 01:16.709
Who should I make
the check out to?

01:16.792 --> 01:18.250
Well, the foundation's
in my name,

01:18.333 --> 01:20.000
so just make it out to me.

01:20.083 --> 01:22.500
Done.

01:24.792 --> 01:26.542
I can't remember
Paul's wife's name.

01:26.625 --> 01:28.792
Oh, you should have used
the rhyming trick, Jen-Pen.

01:28.875 --> 01:30.542
Did you do the rhyming trick?

01:30.625 --> 01:32.333
Not for her,
but I did for Tall Paul

01:32.417 --> 01:34.458
-who buys a ball in a stall.
-Okay.

01:34.542 --> 01:35.500
Here, don't worry,
I got you.

01:35.583 --> 01:37.208
Hey, uh, how do I spell
your name?

01:37.291 --> 01:38.709
Just the way it sounds.

01:38.792 --> 01:41.750
Got it. Then that is how
we are gonna spell it.

01:41.834 --> 01:43.291
Yeah, if you don't do
the rhyming trick

01:43.375 --> 01:44.667
out of the gate,
you're kinda screwed.

01:44.750 --> 01:47.000
Okay. We're still looking
for that checkbook.

01:47.083 --> 01:48.500
Oh, we found it.

01:48.583 --> 01:51.000
Greg, do you not know
what we're doing in here?

01:51.083 --> 01:52.417
I honestly don't.

01:53.834 --> 01:55.583
Are you serious?
None of the other assistants

01:55.667 --> 01:57.333
know Paul's wife's name?

01:57.417 --> 01:59.667
Yeah, of course I know
the other assistants' names.

01:59.750 --> 02:01.834
Yeah, of course
I know your name.

02:01.917 --> 02:03.709
Not today, okay?
Please don't test me.

02:03.792 --> 02:06.667
Yeah, no. We're done here.

02:06.750 --> 02:08.166
You can get back to the funeral.

02:08.250 --> 02:09.875
You want to know what
I've been getting into?

02:09.959 --> 02:11.375
-Genealogy.
-Yeah.

02:11.458 --> 02:12.583
-Mm.
-Did you know

02:12.667 --> 02:14.917
that I'm named after
my great uncle?

02:15.000 --> 02:17.625
But, medically, great aunt.

02:17.709 --> 02:18.917
Yeah, it's kind of like

02:19.000 --> 02:20.542
that movie, <i>Mrs. Doubtfire--</i>
you've seen it.

02:20.625 --> 02:22.792
Except her name was Greg.

02:22.875 --> 02:24.875
You know, I've never seen
<i>Mrs. Doubtfire.</i>

02:24.959 --> 02:26.125
What?

02:26.208 --> 02:28.083
So, are you named after anybody?

02:28.166 --> 02:29.875
Well, you know,
there was this garden

02:29.959 --> 02:31.208
in the home that I grew up in,

02:31.291 --> 02:33.750
so, obviously...

02:33.834 --> 02:36.125
-Pfft, yeah, obviously.
-Obviously.

02:36.208 --> 02:37.458
(laughs)

02:37.542 --> 02:39.458
Ding. Sounds like
the coffee's ready.

02:39.542 --> 02:41.917
-Greg, will you meet me in the kitchen?
-Uh-huh.

02:42.000 --> 02:43.792
Her name is related to a garden.

02:43.875 --> 02:45.166
-Okay,
I'm just gonna throw some out there.
-Okay.

02:45.250 --> 02:46.500
-You tell me if any one lands.
-Yeah.

02:46.583 --> 02:48.000
-Okay, Lily.
-Good.

02:48.083 --> 02:49.041
-Myrtle.
-Yep.

02:49.125 --> 02:50.083
-Fern.
-Maybe.

02:50.166 --> 02:52.208
-Fence.
-No. Yeah, that's a hard pass.

02:52.291 --> 02:53.417
Fence Saltarelli?

02:53.500 --> 02:55.750
I mean,
this is a disaster, Greg.

02:55.834 --> 02:57.667
Like, if she finds out
that we don't know her name

02:57.750 --> 02:59.375
after spending
an entire evening together,

02:59.458 --> 03:00.709
she's gonna hate us.

03:00.792 --> 03:02.417
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

03:02.500 --> 03:04.917
Probably more you, but mm-hmm.

03:06.625 --> 03:08.834
PAUL:
Do I have something in my nose, Bunny?

03:08.917 --> 03:12.125
No. All good. Clear.

03:12.208 --> 03:13.792
Bunny. Her name is Bunny.

03:13.875 --> 03:16.125
<i>Bunny </i>in the garden.
I am very mad

03:16.208 --> 03:17.709
that I did not
come up with that.

03:17.792 --> 03:21.458
Okay, who's ready for coffee?

03:21.542 --> 03:23.542
Bunny, you a regular
or decaf girl?

03:23.625 --> 03:26.750
Uh, regular, I guess.

03:26.834 --> 03:28.417
You sure? 'Cause I can
whip up a pot of decaf

03:28.500 --> 03:29.458
like that, Bunny.

03:29.542 --> 03:32.125
(chuckles) Okay.

03:32.208 --> 03:35.333
Excuse me, I forgot the sugar.

03:35.417 --> 03:36.750
Crap, I got it wrong.

03:36.834 --> 03:37.875
You should have seen
the look he gave her.

03:37.959 --> 03:39.875
I mean, I clearly called her
the wrong name.

03:39.959 --> 03:40.917
This is terrible.

03:41.000 --> 03:42.333
I knew she wasn't a Bunny.

03:42.417 --> 03:44.667
I mean, I didn't want to
say anything, but I knew it.

03:44.750 --> 03:46.542
I just screwed myself
out of making partner

03:46.625 --> 03:48.583
because I couldn't remember
one name.

03:48.667 --> 03:49.709
Now I'm gonna have
to keep parking

03:49.792 --> 03:51.583
between assistant
what's-her-face

03:51.667 --> 03:54.125
and Mrs. Never Flushes.

03:54.208 --> 03:56.792
You know, it's actually
getting a little late.

03:56.875 --> 03:58.625
We're gonna take a pass
on the coffee.

03:58.709 --> 04:01.125
Oh, no, no, stay.
Just-just one cup.

04:01.208 --> 04:03.417
We've got cream, sugar, agave.

04:03.500 --> 04:04.667
You know what I say?
I like it,

04:04.750 --> 04:06.125
I love it,
<i>agave </i>have it.

04:06.208 --> 04:08.208
-Huh?
-We don't have any agave.

04:11.333 --> 04:14.041
Well, damn it, Bunny!

04:14.125 --> 04:15.375
You should have
told me that earlier.

04:15.458 --> 04:16.750
(scoffs) I mean,

04:16.834 --> 04:19.709
Is he a funny bunny or what?
(laughs)

04:19.792 --> 04:22.125
-You call your husband "Bunny"?
-Mm-hmm.

04:22.208 --> 04:25.458
'Cause we were wondering why
you were calling her Bunny.

04:25.542 --> 04:28.000
-Yeah.
-That's my pet name for Rose.

04:28.083 --> 04:30.667
No way. Yeah,
I just call everybody Bunny.

04:30.750 --> 04:32.250
(laughs)

04:32.333 --> 04:33.834
(quietly):
Rose blows her nose
and never shows her toes.

04:33.917 --> 04:35.333
Got it. (clears throat)

04:35.417 --> 04:38.291
-So, you bunnies want to stay for coffee?
-Hmm?

04:38.375 --> 04:40.583
-What the heck, what's one cup?
-Yes.

04:40.667 --> 04:42.250
-Great.
-Great, great. Hey, say, do you, uh...

04:42.333 --> 04:44.792
you have any camp songs
about drinking coffee?

04:44.875 --> 04:46.208
We were children at camp.

04:46.291 --> 04:47.458
We didn't drink coffee.

04:47.542 --> 04:49.917
Yeah. But we did drink
bug juice!

04:50.000 --> 04:51.625
-Oh! Bug juice!
-(laughs)

04:51.709 --> 04:55.333
So, did you go
to sleepaway camp, Peter?

04:55.417 --> 04:57.166
-Uh...
-Uh...

04:57.250 --> 05:01.500
Yeah, Peter, uh, went
to break-dancing camp.

05:10.542 --> 05:12.291
Oh. Oh, you just getting home?

05:12.375 --> 05:15.500
I was just, uh, checking the
expiration date on the mustard.

05:15.583 --> 05:18.291
Still got two months,
but that'll sneak up on us.

05:18.375 --> 05:20.291
I'm sorry that I didn't text you
back last night.

05:20.375 --> 05:21.333
-Oh.
-I lost my phone

05:21.417 --> 05:23.291
in the dugout at Dodger Stadium.

05:23.375 --> 05:25.041
Crazy night.

05:25.125 --> 05:27.834
It turns out the players
are super nice, by the way.

05:27.917 --> 05:29.667
Yeah. They seem really nice
on TV.

05:29.750 --> 05:30.709
Yeah.

05:30.792 --> 05:33.166
Hey, uh, next time,

05:33.250 --> 05:34.583
maybe we could just have
a signal

05:34.667 --> 05:36.041
so that I know you're okay.

05:36.125 --> 05:38.250
That signal could be
that you text me back.

05:38.333 --> 05:39.333
Totally.

05:39.417 --> 05:41.291
Hey, when you first said

05:41.375 --> 05:43.208
that we should break up, I...

05:43.291 --> 05:47.458
wasn't so sure, but I am
learning so much about myself.

05:47.542 --> 05:50.125
Like, it turns out
I'm super funny!

05:50.208 --> 05:52.041
Guys laugh at everything I say,

05:52.125 --> 05:53.834
even when I don't understand
the joke.

05:53.917 --> 05:55.625
-(chuckles)
-See? (giggles)

05:55.709 --> 05:56.875
Look at me.

05:56.959 --> 05:59.375
Yeah. Look at you.

06:02.375 --> 06:04.291
Where's Clementine, anyway?

06:04.375 --> 06:07.417
The Dodgers have an away game,
and, evidently, she's good luck.

06:07.500 --> 06:09.417
Oh, yeah, that's the dream.

06:09.500 --> 06:11.417
To be a young, nubile woman.

06:11.500 --> 06:12.959
And so funny!

06:13.041 --> 06:14.166
-(chuckling): Right?
-Yeah.

06:14.250 --> 06:15.417
She's... (chuckles)

06:15.500 --> 06:16.834
But what you got's not bad.

06:16.917 --> 06:18.458
You got to get out there
and let the ladies know

06:18.542 --> 06:19.792
you're down to clown.

06:19.875 --> 06:22.709
I'm respecting the honeymoon
period of our divorce.

06:22.792 --> 06:24.959
I think Clementine and I
should take some time

06:25.041 --> 06:26.709
and examine our feelings.

06:26.792 --> 06:29.709
Oh, feelings are what got you
in this mess in the first place.

06:29.792 --> 06:33.208
Marriage, responsibilities,
that stupid house.

06:33.291 --> 06:34.792
Man, get out there
and have some fun.

06:34.875 --> 06:36.458
No strings attached.

06:36.542 --> 06:37.792
I don't know if I'm ready.

06:37.875 --> 06:39.667
You listen to me.

06:39.750 --> 06:41.500
You take it from a man
who also got married too soon.

06:41.583 --> 06:43.667
You never get these years
of freedom back.

06:44.500 --> 06:45.750
Now, I love your mother.

06:45.834 --> 06:47.000
-(chuckles) You know?
-Uh-huh.

06:47.083 --> 06:49.959
Very happy with the choices
I've made, but...

06:50.041 --> 06:51.959
if I had a chance
to do it all over again,

06:52.041 --> 06:53.208
I'd do it a little different.

06:53.291 --> 06:54.959
And I'd do a lot more of it.

06:55.041 --> 06:56.041
You know?

06:56.125 --> 06:57.083
Again, love your mom.

06:57.166 --> 06:58.333
Very happy.

06:58.417 --> 07:00.333
But you got to get out there.

07:00.417 --> 07:03.000
You got to live life
for both of us.

07:06.667 --> 07:08.667
(both moaning)

07:08.750 --> 07:10.041
(objects clattering)

07:10.125 --> 07:11.917
Oh, I am so glad we matched.

07:12.000 --> 07:13.667
I thought an app for divorcees

07:13.750 --> 07:16.166
was gonna be filled with
a bunch of lonely losers.

07:16.250 --> 07:19.291
God, it is just so fascinating
to meet someone

07:19.375 --> 07:21.667
who's this naturally smooth.

07:21.750 --> 07:23.041
Oh, thank you. (chuckles)

07:23.125 --> 07:25.166
I love that we have
so much in common:

07:25.250 --> 07:27.542
still living with our exes,
just got on the market,

07:27.625 --> 07:29.417
not looking
for anything serious.

07:29.500 --> 07:33.500
Yes! Let's just go crazy
and have fun, you know?

07:33.583 --> 07:35.250
We all have HPV anyway.

07:35.333 --> 07:37.291
-We do?
-Oh, yeah.

07:37.375 --> 07:39.500
So, you're so smooth.

07:39.583 --> 07:41.083
Okay.

07:42.125 --> 07:43.834
(gasps) Two mugs.

07:43.917 --> 07:46.542
-(laughs)
-We did it! We did it!

07:46.625 --> 07:47.959
Oh, wait, did we do it,
or are we just telling people

07:48.041 --> 07:49.083
we did?
Doesn't matter to me.

07:49.166 --> 07:50.792
-No. We did it.
-Yes!

07:50.875 --> 07:53.625
-This is for Alex.
-Alex! Oh, buddy.

07:53.709 --> 07:55.166
Oh!

07:55.250 --> 07:56.792
-Ah, she sounds hot.
-Yeah.

07:56.875 --> 07:58.625
I mean... "she," right?

07:58.709 --> 08:00.166
Not that it matters.
Doesn't matter.

08:00.250 --> 08:01.750
Just want you to have fun,

08:01.834 --> 08:03.917
'cause this is the life
that we were meant to lead.

08:04.000 --> 08:05.417
Thank you, Dad.

08:05.500 --> 08:06.834
No, thank <i>you.</i>

08:06.917 --> 08:09.083
This is...
a one-night stand for man,

08:09.166 --> 08:12.834
and one giant-night stand
for mankind! (chuckles)

08:14.625 --> 08:16.542
I love your mother,
and I would never choose

08:16.625 --> 08:18.208
to do anything different.

08:18.291 --> 08:19.250
Okay.

08:19.333 --> 08:21.125
<i>-Yeah, </i>okay.
-I can go?

08:21.208 --> 08:22.291
All right.

08:22.375 --> 08:24.542
-Get out of here.
-(chuckles)

08:24.625 --> 08:26.250
(door opens)

08:26.333 --> 08:27.625
(door closes)

08:27.709 --> 08:28.792
(sighs)

08:28.875 --> 08:30.125
(whispers):
Man.

08:30.208 --> 08:31.166
♪ ♪

08:31.250 --> 08:32.417
ALEX:
Oh.

08:32.500 --> 08:33.458
Hold on.

08:33.542 --> 08:34.667
Hi.

08:34.750 --> 08:35.917
So, I, uh,

08:36.000 --> 08:37.500
borrowed one of your shirts.

08:37.583 --> 08:39.583
Hope that's okay.
It's a little,

08:39.667 --> 08:42.875
-uh, tight on me.
-Yeah, I have really narrow shoulders.

08:42.959 --> 08:45.667
Oh, well, easier
to wrap my arms around you.

08:45.750 --> 08:48.083
You're like a sexy...

08:48.166 --> 08:49.917
string cheese.

08:50.000 --> 08:54.083
And I cannot wait to peel
off another piece tonight.

08:54.166 --> 08:56.125
Sure. Why don't we make
a weekend of it?

08:56.208 --> 08:58.709
Great. Go ahead and change
the locks, you son of a bitch.

08:58.792 --> 09:00.667
The kids and I have
a place to stay.

09:00.750 --> 09:01.875
(sets phone down)

09:01.959 --> 09:03.500
Whew! Coffee. Yes, please.

09:03.583 --> 09:04.792
(chuckles weakly)

09:04.875 --> 09:06.709
-Thank you.
-Sure.

09:06.792 --> 09:08.000
I got you! (grunts)

09:08.083 --> 09:09.709
-Hey, no running, please.
-(imitates gun firing)

09:09.792 --> 09:12.291
Gosh, guys, I told you not
to leave your clothes here.

09:12.375 --> 09:17.041
Mom, this doesn't taste
like our apple juice.

09:17.125 --> 09:18.667
Oh.

09:19.500 --> 09:22.125
I need someone to wipe me!

09:22.208 --> 09:23.667
Honey, can you do it?

09:23.750 --> 09:25.125
I got the last one.

09:25.208 --> 09:26.166
Oh.

09:26.250 --> 09:27.333
♪ ♪

09:29.500 --> 09:31.417
Oh, here he comes,

09:31.500 --> 09:33.333
barely standing--
I like the look of this.

09:33.417 --> 09:36.041
I haven't slept--
they kept me up all night.

09:37.000 --> 09:38.750
Do we have any sippy cups?

09:38.834 --> 09:40.750
"They"? "Sippy cups"?

09:40.834 --> 09:42.542
Ooh, you nasty! Come on.

09:49.834 --> 09:51.166
-Wait, w-wait.
-Huh?

09:51.250 --> 09:52.625
What if we didn't?

09:52.709 --> 09:54.458
Have sex?
Colleen, we've been married

09:54.542 --> 09:56.583
for, like, two seconds--
we can't start that now.

09:56.667 --> 09:59.250
No. Use protection.

09:59.333 --> 10:02.208
No shirts, all skins.

10:02.291 --> 10:03.333
Seriously?

10:03.417 --> 10:04.458
-Yeah.
-But I thought

10:04.542 --> 10:06.417
we were gonna wait
until your horoscope said

10:06.500 --> 10:07.917
whatever dumb things
horoscopes say.

10:08.000 --> 10:10.500
Well, yeah. But then
I fell off the balcony,

10:10.583 --> 10:13.542
and I realized that life doesn't
always allow you to make plans.

10:13.625 --> 10:16.875
We both want a family, and
we're not getting any younger.

10:16.959 --> 10:19.667
-I can't believe we're gonna do this.
-I know.

10:19.750 --> 10:21.166
I love you so much.

10:21.250 --> 10:22.417
I love you, too.

10:22.500 --> 10:24.917
♪ ♪

10:27.208 --> 10:28.834
(takes deep breath)

10:28.917 --> 10:30.625
Mmm...

10:30.709 --> 10:33.041
(drawer slides open)

10:33.125 --> 10:35.458
(groans, yawns)

10:35.542 --> 10:38.375
Hey, baby. Why you packin'?

10:38.458 --> 10:40.375
Well, we have to be ready
to go to the hospital.

10:40.458 --> 10:42.125
I could go into labor
at any minute.

10:43.834 --> 10:45.625
Whoa!

10:45.709 --> 10:48.583
How can you be pregnant already?
We just had sex last night.

10:48.667 --> 10:50.959
(laughs):
That's how it works, Matt.

10:51.041 --> 10:52.750
I thought there
would be more time.

10:52.834 --> 10:53.834
And I don't know

10:53.917 --> 10:55.375
anything about having a baby.

10:55.458 --> 10:58.000
We need a baby room,
and we can't afford to move.

10:58.083 --> 11:00.375
We've already moved, silly.

11:00.458 --> 11:01.458
♪ ♪

11:01.542 --> 11:04.625
Welcome back to the garage,
dear.

11:04.709 --> 11:06.875
Stay as long as you want.

11:06.959 --> 11:09.542
Just maybe don't breathe
too deeply

11:09.625 --> 11:10.583
near the paint

11:10.667 --> 11:13.041
or the gas or the rat feces.

11:13.125 --> 11:14.750
It might not be good
for that baby.

11:14.834 --> 11:15.959
COLLEEN:
John, that mobile

11:16.041 --> 11:18.583
-is perfect.
-Thanks.

11:18.667 --> 11:20.667
Just a few things
I had laying around.

11:20.750 --> 11:22.125
(Colleen and John's
echoing laughter)

11:22.208 --> 11:24.458
Um, we're not
gonna be staying long.

11:24.542 --> 11:26.458
